synthases (PKS II), are a large class of structurally diverse natural products.1 They exhibit a broad spectrum of medicinally important activities, including antibacterial, antifungal, and anticancer properties.2 In the course of our screening program for new antibiotics,3−5 we used a polymerase chain reaction- based approach, targeting the type II ketosynthase gene,6 in order to identify potential aromatic polyketide-producing microoganisms.7 This led to the rapid identiﬁcation of the from marine-derived actinomycete Saccharothrix sp. 10-10, which tetracenomycin (Tcm) X,8 an aromatic polyketide identiﬁed as a major metabolite in our antibiotic, was preliminary study.7 Tcms are a family of tetracyclic naphthacenequinones with a highly hydroxylated cyclohex- enone moiety and signiﬁcant antitumor activity,9 which has in their biosynthesis.10 An sparked considerable interest extensive investigation of the secondary metabolite composi- tion of this strain has aﬀorded three novel seco-tetracenomycins, saccharothrixones A−C (1−3), and saccharothrixone D (4), a new Tcm analogue with opposite conﬁgurations at all stereocenters. Herein, we report details of the isolation, characterization, and biological activities of these compounds. Saccharothrixone A (1) was isolated as a white powder with the molecular formula C23H22O11 as determined by HRESIMS. ABSTRACT: Saccharothrixones A−C (1−3), three new aromatic polyketide seco-tetracenomycins, and saccharothrixone D (4), a new tetracenomycin analogue possessing opposite conﬁgurations at all of the stereogenic centers, were isolated from the marine-derived actino- mycete Saccharothrix sp. 10-10. Compounds 1−3 represent the ﬁrst examples of seco-tetracenomycins where the quinone ring B is cleaved and re-formed into a furanone ring. Their structures were elucidated by spectroscopic analyses and ECD calculations. The absolute conﬁg- uration of 4 was conﬁrmed by single-crystal X-ray diﬀraction analysis. Saccharothrixone D (4) showed in vitro cytotoxic activity against the HepG2 cancer cell line with an IC50 value of 7.5 μM. © XXXX American Chemical Society and American Society of Pharmacognosy Qiang Wang, and Chunling Xiao*,†

The presence of three carbonyl groups and six oleﬁnic groups accounted for nine of the 13 degrees of unsaturation required by the molecular formula, therefore illustrating the existence of four rings in 1. Detailed comparison of the NMR data of 1 with those of Tcm X (Table S1, Supporting Information) revealed the similarity of the resonance signals in rings C and D, but signiﬁcant diﬀerences in rings A and B.7,11 This suggested that 1 was an unusual Tcm analogue, for which the structure was further elucidated by 2D NMR spectroscopic analysis.

The HSQC experiment allowed assignments of the hydro- gen-bearing carbon and corresponding proton resonances in the NMR spectra. The HMBC spectrum of 1 showed two- and three-bond correlations (Figure 1) from H-4 to C-4a, C-5, C- 8a, and C-9a; from H-5 to C-4, C-6, C-7, and C-8a; from H3-11 to C-7, C-8, and C-8a; and from the methoxy protons at δ H 3.97 and 3.91 to C-6 and C-10, respectively. In addition, four- bond correlations from H-4 to C-9; from H-5 to C-8 and C-10; and from H3-11 to C-9 and C-10 were observed in the HMBC spectrum. These correlations, in combination with the chemical shifts of the proton and carbon resonances, indicated the presence of a naphthalene ring moiety consisting of C-3a−C-9a with a methoxy, a methoxycarbonyl, a methyl, and a hydroxy respectively. The ECD spectra of four possible isomers (1a−1d, Figure S39) were calculated using the TDDFT method and then compared with the experimental data. The calculated ECD spectrum for the 3S,12R,13R,17S- diastereomer (1a) was in good agreement with the experimental ECD curve (Figures 2a and S39), allowing the absolute conﬁguration of 1 to be assigned as 3S,12R,13R,17S. formula of saccharothrixone B (2) was elucidated as C24H24O11 by HRESIMS, with one CH2 unit greater than that of 1. The NMR data of 2 were similar to those of 1, except for the presence of one additional methoxy group [δ C 61.1] in 2. In addition, the resonance for H-13 in 2 was shifted by Δδ −0.40, as compared with that of 1, whereas the resonance for C-13 was shifted by Δδ +8.7. This indicates that the hydroxy group at C-13 in 1 was replaced by a methoxy group in 2, which was evidenced by 2D NMR data analysis (Figure S1). The relative and absolute conﬁgurations of 2 were deduced to be the same as those of 1 based on their similar ROESY correlations and ECD curves (Figures S1 and S2). This was also supported by TDDFT-ECD calculations for 2 (Figures 2b and S40).

The molecular formula for saccharothrixone C (3) was determined as C24H24O11, a formula isomeric with 2, by HRESIMS data. The 1H NMR data indicated very close similarities between the two compounds, but there were some obvious diﬀerences, in particular, the shielded nature of the resonances for H-13 (δ H 3.28) in 3 compared to the corresponding signals (δ H 4.42 and 3.73, respectively) in 2 and the deshielded signal for H-17 (δ H 4.62 in 3 vs 3.88 in 2). In addition, comparison of the 13C NMR data of 3 and 2 showed that C-3 and C-13 in 3 were shifted by Δδ +1.6 and +2.2, respectively, whereas C-14 and C-17 were signiﬁcantly shielded. The diﬀerences in the NMR data of 3 and 2 were mainly associated with the three stereogenic centers C- suggesting that 3 had signiﬁcant 3, C-13, and C-17, conﬁgurational diﬀerences at these positions. Analysis of the HSQC and HMBC data revealed that 3 possessed the same planar structure as 2. The correlation of H-3/H-17 in the ROESY spectrum of 3 (Figure S1) in DMSO-d6 demonstrated that these two protons in 3 were on the same side of ring A. However, the correlations of H-3/H-13 and H-13/H-17 observed in 2 were absent for 3 in ROESY spectra recorded in both acetone-d6 and DMSO-d6, suggesting that H-13 in 3

was on the other side of ring A. The ECD spectrum of 3 showed two positive CEs at 300 and 246 nm and two negative CEs at 265 and 226 nm. The observed negative CE at 265 nm in 3, corresponding to the n → π* transition of the α,β- unsaturated γ-lactone,13 was opposite that in 2, indicating a change in conﬁguration at C-3 in 3. To resolve the absolute conﬁguration of 3, we again employed TDDFT methods to calculate the ECD spectra of four possible diastereomers (Figures 2c and S41). Comparison of the experimental and calculated ECD spectra showed excellent agreement for the 3R,12R,13S,17S-conﬁguration for 3. As seen from the optimized lowest energy conformers (Figures S45 and S47) using the DFT method at the B3LYP/6-31G(d,p) level, the conﬁguration change at C-3 in 3 resulted in the orientation of H-13 and 13-OMe under the anisotropic shielding region of the naphthalene ring.14 This explains why the signals for H-13 and 13-OMe in 3 were dramatically shielded in relation to those in 2.

Saccharothrixone D (4) was obtained as yellow needles with the molecular formula C24H22O11. Analysis of 1H and 13C NMR data (Tables 2 and S1) suggested that 4 is an isomer of Tcm X.7,8 The main diﬀerence is attributed to ring A, in which the oxo group at C-1 and the double bond between C-2 and C-3 in Tcm X are transferred to C-3 and between C-1 and C-2 in 4, respectively. Further analysis of the 2D NMR data of 4 revealed the planar the relative conﬁguration of 4 could not be elucidated by the ROESY data due to lack of key deﬁnitive correlations. Interestingly, the ECD spectrum of 4 was found to be almost the mirror image of those of Tcm X (Figure S2) and other Tcm derivatives,7,15 suggesting that the conﬁguration of 4 was opposite those of the known Tcms. Finally, the structure of 4 was solved by single- crystal X-ray diﬀraction analysis using Cu Kα radiation. The crystal structure (Figure 3) demonstrated that 4-OMe, 4a-OH, and 12a-OH were oriented on the same face of the ring. The absolute conﬁgurations at the stereogenic centers were determined to be 4R, 4aS, 12aS on the basis of the anomalous dispersion with a Flack parameter of 0.01(7)16 and a Hooft parameter of −0.02(7).17 In addition, comparison of the experimental and the calculated ECD spectra for 4 further supported this assignment (Figure S42). The absolute conﬁguration of Tcm C and its derivatives, elloramycins, had been established as 4S, 4aR, 12aR by X-ray crystallography and chemical methods.9,18 Saccharothrixone D (4) is the ﬁrst identiﬁed Tcm analogue that possesses completely opposite conﬁgurations at all stereogenic centers.

The biosynthesis of the Tcms has been extensively studied, leading to the identiﬁcation of several biosynthetic intermedi- ates and shunt products.10 Saccharothrixones A−C (1−3) possess a novel seco-tetracenomycin skeleton, where the quinone B ring is cleaved and re-formed into a furanone ring. A hypothetical biosynthetic pathway is postulated in Scheme 1. Scheme 1. Plausible Biosynthesis Pathway for Saccharothrixones A−C (1−3)

They might be derived from a post-PKS tailoring pathway with Tcm C as a precursor.9,10,19 Ketoreduction at C-5 in Tcm C would generate the pair of intermediates (5S)-5a and (5R)-5b, which then could undergo intramolecular nucleophilic addition and simultaneous cleavage to produce 1 and its isomer 1′, respectively. O-Methylation at C-12a of 1 and 1′ would ﬁnally give 2 and 3, respectively. During the C−C bond cleavage of C- 12/C-12a, the protonation of C-12a by the enzyme might occur on the side opposite 5-OH of ring B because of less steric hindrance. Consequently, this would result in retention of conﬁguration at C-12a in 1 and 2 but inversion of conﬁguration in 3. In addition, it is important to note that saccharothrixone D (4) possesses the conﬁguration opposite those of known Tcms and the related elloramycins.9,18 This is unusual, as most polyketide post-tailoring reactions have been found to be stereospeciﬁc.19,20 Shen et al. have established that the three hydroxy groups at C-4, C-4a, and C-12a in the Tcms are introduced via a cis-triple hydroxylation of Tcm A2, catalyzed by the Tcm A2 oxygenase.21−23 Saccharothrixone D (4) may be DOI: 10.1021/acs.jnatprod.5b00577 J. Nat. Prod. XXXX, XXX, XXX−XXX Journal of Natural Products

a shunt product derived from Tcm D3 (Scheme S1).10 In contrast to the main pathway,10,21,22 the Tcm A2 oxygenase might bind the planar Tcm D3 in the inverted orientation in the biosynthesis of 4. As a result, the enzyme-catalyzed cis-triple hydroxylation could take place on the other side of the Tcm D3 plane, resulting in the opposite conﬁgurations at C-4, C-4a, and C-12a in 4. The co-isolation of 4 and Tcm X from Saccharothrix sp. 10-10 may provide new insights into the stereospeciﬁcity of the oxygenase in the biosynthesis of Tcms.

Producing Microorganism and Fermentation. The producing microorganism, Saccharothrix sp. 10-10, was isolated from a marine sediment sample collected at a depth of ca. 40 m from Heishijiao Bay, Dalian, China, in 2010. The strain was identiﬁed as a member of the genus Saccharothrix on the basis of 16S rRNA gene sequence analysis (GenBank accession number JQ782931). It shared high sequence identity with other Saccharothrix strains, including 99.9% with S. longispora (GenBank NR041738) and 99.5% with S. yanglingensis (GenBank NR117283). Strain 10-10 was grown on ISP4 medium (BD Diagnostics) agar plates for about 10 days at 28 °C and then inoculated into 300 replicate 500 mL Fernbach ﬂasks each containing 100 mL of sterile fermentation medium (composed of 10 g of starch, 25 g of glucose, 10 g of cottonseed ﬂour, 3 g of peptone, 5 g of CaCO3, 0.1 g of KH2PO4, 0.1 g of MgSO4, and 5 g of NaCl in 1 L of H2O) and cultured on rotary shakers (200 rpm) at 28 °C for 5 days.

Isolation. The culture broth (30 L) was separated into the mycelia and the supernatant by centrifugation. The mycelial cake was extracted four times with acetone to aﬀord an organic cell extract. The supernatant was then subjected to a Diaion HP-20 macroporous adsorbent resin column (6 L), and the column was washed with H2O and then successively eluted with 50% and 80% aqueous acetone. The two latter fractions were combined with the organic cell extract and then concentrated under reduced pressure to aﬀord an aqueous solution. The aqueous solution was extracted three times with EtOAc, and the solvent was evaporated under vacuum to give the EtOAc extract (59 g).
